"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112694"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two hour history of sudden onset severe shortness of breath and sharp, central chest pain. She has had a sore throat and runny nose since being discharged home from hospital two days ago after having total knee reconstruction three days before that. She has a medical history of osteoarthritis, type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her medications include amlodipine, metformin and paracetamol. She received prophylactic enoxaparin whilst in hospital.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed and is using accessory muscles to breathe. Her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 85/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 32/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated and heart sounds are normal. Her chest is clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumonia","Myocardial infarction","Massive pulmonary embolism","Aortic dissection","Pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of massive pulmonary embolism (PE). The combination of acute onset dyspnoea, chest pain, hypoxia, and haemodynamic compromise, along with significant risk factors (recent knee surgery), makes this the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops over days rather than hours and usually presents with fever, productive cough, and focal chest signs on examination. The acute onset and clear chest examination make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with central chest pain radiating to the left arm or jaw, often associated with nausea and sweating. While it can cause shortness of breath and hypotension, the pleuritic nature of the pain and hypoxia make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMassive pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute cardiorespiratory compromise. Recent orthopaedic surgery is a major risk factor, even with appropriate prophylaxis. The elevated jugular venous pressure suggests right heart strain, which occurs with significant clot burden.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden severe tearing chest pain radiating to the back, often associated with asymmetric pulses or blood pressure readings. While it can cause hypotension, the pleuritic nature of the pain and hypoxia make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with positional chest pain that is worse when lying flat and improved by sitting forward. While it can cause pleuritic pain, it rarely causes significant hypoxia or hypotension unless there is cardiac tamponade, which would cause muffled heart sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recent surgery, particularly orthopaedic procedures, is a major risk factor for pulmonary embolism.","The classic triad of pulmonary embolism includes acute dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, and hypoxia.","Tachycardia and hypotension in pulmonary embolism suggest a massive clot burden affecting right heart function."],"references":["Morrone D, Morrone V. Acute Pulmonary Embolism: Focus on the Clinical Picture. Korean Circ J. 2018 May;48(5):365-381. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29737640/","Doherty S. Pulmonary embolism: an update. Australian Family Physician. 2017;46(11). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/november/pulmonary-embolism"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94727"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94727"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-03T17:26:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T17:54:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7841"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112694"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated